  "prompt": "Why I cannot use netsend commands?",
  "response": "As of Windows Vista and later versions, the `netsend` command was removed from the operating system. The `netsend` command was used in older versions of Windows (like Windows XP and Windows 2000) to send messages to other users, computers, or messaging names on the network.\n\nIf you need similar functionality in more current versions of Windows, you can use the `msg` command, which is designed to send messages to users on a network. Here is an example of how to use the `msg` command:\n\n```shell\nmsg * /server:[servername] /time:[seconds] [message]\n```\n\nReplace `[servername]` with the name of the server, `[seconds]` with the number of seconds you want the message to be displayed, and `[message]` with the actual message you want to send.\n\nAdditionally, for more advanced messaging and communication needs, there are various third-party software solutions and messaging apps that can be used depending on your requirements.",
